Φ(Ecological_Memory) = σ(archive-distinction|world-as-repository) ∘ ρ(land-resonance|terrain-recitation-feedback) ∘ λ(forgetting-pressure|amnesia-intensity) ∘ β(ritual-growth|anchoring-emergence) ∘ δγ(soil-memory|spiritcode-substrate) ∘ μ(persistence-structure|encoded-endurance) + ε | :remembering

# ── σ | Air | Aerunik ──
# σ(archive-distinction|world-as-repository) — emphasis 0.16
# The perceptual shift that recognizes landscape as archive rather than backdrop.
# Air-element distinction between a world that merely exists and a world that remembers.
# "This world... it doesn't forget." The environment knows more about us than we know
# about ourselves.

# ── ρ | Water | Sentaria ──
# ρ(land-resonance|terrain-recitation-feedback) — emphasis 0.18
# The terrain recites memory back to those who know how to listen. Water-element
# resonance between human attention and landscape intelligence — ecological listening
# as reciprocal flow. The land holds memory and releases it through encounter.

# ── λ | Fire | Jvalion ──
# λ(forgetting-pressure|amnesia-intensity) — emphasis 0.12
# Modern disconnection from ecological memory as Fire-element pressure — the intensity
# of forgetting, the speed of amnesia in industrial civilization. The Forgetter who
# tries to outrun the past only to find the terrain itself reciting it back.

# ── β | Wood | Arboriel ──
# β(ritual-growth|anchoring-emergence) — emphasis 0.16
# Ritual anchoring as recovery protocol: practices that reconnect human awareness with
# ecological memory through deliberate, repeated engagement. Wood-element growth through
# ceremonial and attentive return to the land that holds what we cannot.

# ── δγ | Earth | Humavita ──
# δγ(soil-memory|spiritcode-substrate) — emphasis 0.24
# The dominant element: soil, stone, cambium, and brine as physical substrate of
# ecological memory. Spiritcodes embedded in terrain — material encoding of information
# that persists long after the beings who created it collapse into amnesia.

# ── μ | Metal | Ferrosid ──
# μ(persistence-structure|encoded-endurance) — emphasis 0.14
# The structural capacity of ecological systems to encode and preserve information
# across time. Seed banks, mycorrhizal networks, geological strata — Metal-element
# persistence that maintains pattern through disturbance.

# Z-STATE: :remembering
# The system is in an active state of remembering — not passive storage but ongoing
# recitation, where landscape continuously offers its memory to those capable of
# ecological listening.

# TENDENCY: δγ → 0.24
# Earth-dominant tendency reflects the primacy of material substrate — soil, stone,
# and living tissue — as the medium through which ecological memory persists.
